.\" do-snapshot.1 - DigitalOcean Snapshot Tool for FreeBSD
.\" Man page in mdoc(7) format — render with: man ./do-snapshot.1
.\"
.Dd April 10, 2026
.Dt DO-SNAPSHOT 1
.Os FreeBSD
.
.Sh NAME
.Nm do-snapshot
.Nd automated DigitalOcean droplet snapshot tool for FreeBSD
.
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl t Ar token
.Op Fl k Ar keep
.Op Fl n Ar prefix
.Op Fl p
.Op Fl v
.Op Fl h
.Op Ar droplet
.
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
creates and manages snapshots of DigitalOcean droplets via the
DigitalOcean API v2.
It is written in pure POSIX
.Xr sh 1
and uses
.Xr fetch 1
from the FreeBSD base system as its HTTP client.
.Pp
When run on a droplet,
.Nm
auto-detects the current droplet ID via the DigitalOcean metadata
endpoint
.Pq 169.254.169.254
and snapshots only that droplet.
When run on a remote host, it lists and snapshots all droplets
accessible by the supplied API token, or the single droplet identified
by the optional
.Ar droplet
argument.
.Pp
After each snapshot is created, old snapshots whose names match the
configured prefix are pruned so that at most
.Ar keep
snapshots are retained per droplet.
.Pp
The following options are available:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Fl t Ar token
DigitalOcean personal access token with read and write scope.
If not supplied,
.Ev DO_API_TOKEN
is read from the environment.
.It Fl k Ar keep
Number of snapshots to keep per droplet.
Oldest snapshots beyond this count are deleted.
Defaults to
.Sy 7 .
.It Fl n Ar prefix
Prefix used when naming new snapshots and when identifying existing
snapshots for retention enforcement.
Snapshots whose names do not begin with this prefix are never deleted.
Defaults to
.Sy auto .
.It Fl p
Power off the droplet gracefully before taking the snapshot, then
power it back on afterwards.
A graceful
.Sy shutdown
action is attempted first; if the droplet has not reached the
.Sy off
state within 120 seconds a hard
.Sy power_off
is issued.
By default snapshots are taken live.
.It Fl v
Enable verbose debug output to stderr.
.It Fl h
Print a usage summary and exit.
.It Ar droplet
Optional name or numeric ID of a single droplet to snapshot.
When omitted, all reachable droplets are processed
.Pq or only the current droplet when run on a droplet .
.El
.
.Sh SNAPSHOT NAMING
Snapshots are named using the pattern:
.Pp
.D1 Ar prefix Ns - Ns Ar droplet-name Ns - Ns Ar timestamp
.Pp
where
.Ar timestamp
is a UTC ISO\~8601 value of the form
.Sy YYYYMMDDTHHMMSSz .
Example:
.Pp
.D1 auto-web-prod-01-20240410T120000Z
.
.Sh RETENTION POLICY
Only snapshots whose names begin with the configured
.Fl n Ar prefix
are counted and eligible for deletion.
Snapshots created outside
.Nm
are never touched.
.Pp
After a new snapshot is confirmed complete, snapshots are sorted by
creation time ascending.
If the total count exceeds
.Fl k Ar keep ,
the oldest
.Pq total\ \-\ keep
snapshots are deleted via the API.
.
.Sh PERIODIC INTEGRATION
.Nm
integrates with
.Xr periodic 8 .
Install it as a daily job:
.Pp
.Dl cp do-snapshot.sh /usr/local/etc/periodic/daily/500.do-snapshot
.Dl chmod +x /usr/local/etc/periodic/daily/500.do-snapshot
.Pp
Then configure it in
.Pa /etc/periodic.conf :
.Bd -literal -offset indent
do_snapshot_enable="YES"
DO_API_TOKEN="your_token_here"
do_snapshot_keep=7
do_snapshot_prefix="auto"
do_snapshot_poweroff="NO"
do_snapshot_verbose="NO"
.Ed
.Pp
The job honours the
.Va do_snapshot_enable
knob; set it to
.Sy YES
to activate it.
Output is captured by
.Xr periodic 8
and mailed to root only if any output is produced.
.
.Sh ENVIRONMENT
.Bl -tag -width DO_API_TOKEN
.It Ev DO_API_TOKEN
DigitalOcean personal access token.
Used when
.Fl t
is not supplied.
.It Va do_snapshot_enable
Consumed by
.Xr periodic 8 .
Set to
.Sy YES
to enable the daily job.
.It Va do_snapshot_keep
Default retention count.
Equivalent to
.Fl k .
.It Va do_snapshot_prefix
Default snapshot name prefix.
Equivalent to
.Fl n .
.It Va do_snapshot_poweroff
Set to
.Sy YES
to enable power-off mode by default.
Equivalent to
.Fl p .
.It Va do_snapshot_verbose
Set to
.Sy YES
to enable verbose logging by default.
Equivalent to
.Fl v .
.El
.
.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -width /usr/local/etc/periodic/daily/500.do-snapshot
.It Pa /usr/local/bin/do-snapshot
Recommended installation path for interactive use.
.It Pa /usr/local/etc/periodic/daily/500.do-snapshot
Recommended installation path for
.Xr periodic 8
daily execution.
.It Pa /etc/periodic.conf
System-wide
.Xr periodic 8
configuration file.
.It Pa /etc/periodic.conf.local
Local overrides for
.Xr periodic 8
configuration.
.El
.
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Pp
A non-zero exit status indicates that at least one snapshot action
failed.
Individual droplet failures do not abort processing of remaining
droplets.
.
.Sh EXAMPLES
Snapshot the current droplet using the token from the environment,
keeping the default of 7 snapshots:
.Pp
.Dl DO_API_TOKEN=mytoken do-snapshot.sh
.Pp
Snapshot all droplets accessible by the token, keeping only the 3 most
recent snapshots each, with verbose output:
.Pp
.Dl do-snapshot.sh -t mytoken -k 3 -v
.Pp
Snapshot a specific droplet by name:
.Pp
.Dl do-snapshot.sh -t mytoken web-prod-01
.Pp
Power off before snapshot and use a custom prefix:
.Pp
.Dl do-snapshot.sh -t mytoken -p -n nightly
.Pp
Test the
.Xr periodic 8
job manually:
.Pp
.Dl /usr/local/etc/periodic/daily/500.do-snapshot
.Pp
Verify the API token is valid:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
fetch -q -o - \\
    --header "Authorization: Bearer $DO_API_TOKEN" \\
    https://api.digitalocean.com/v2/account | jq .
.Ed
.
.Sh DIAGNOSTICS
.Bl -diag
.It "No API token. Set DO_API_TOKEN or use -t TOKEN."
Neither the
.Fl t
flag nor the
.Ev DO_API_TOKEN
environment variable was provided.
.It "Required command not found: jq"
Install
.Xr jq 1
with
.Ic pkg install jq .
.It "Action NNNN failed."
The DigitalOcean API reported an error for the snapshot action.
Check the droplet status in the DigitalOcean control panel.
.It "Timed out waiting for action NNNN"
The snapshot action did not complete within 3600 seconds.
Large droplets may require more time; verify the action status via the
API or control panel.
.It "Shutdown timeout \(em forcing power-off."
The droplet did not shut down gracefully within 120 seconds.
A hard power-off was issued.
.El
.
